721243f-a.title: Manhattan: Madison Avenue - 27th Street (East)
721243f-a.text:
Madison Avenue, east side, at E. 27th Street, showing un-
known (to the writer) individuals leaving the old Madison Square
Garden (right). The photographer is wiewing northeastward to show
at the left buildings on the north side of E. 27th Street to the
east of Madison Avenue.
prior to 1923.

721246f-a.title: Manhattan: Madison Avenue - 27th Street (East)
721246f-a.text:
Madison Ave., east side, south from and including East 27th Street.
The view shows the old Midison Square Garden, with the Yiddish Art Theatre
occupying the N.W. corner.
August 13, 1924.
Eugene L, Armbruster, Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

721245f-a.title: Manhattan: Madison Avenue - 27th Street (East)
721245f-a.text:
Madison Avenue, S.W. corner of 27th Street, showing New York Jockey
Club House, demolished before 1V10.
Ne view is west on 27th Street. The arch shown st the left of the
picture is part of Madison Scuare Garden (1890-1925). The small
buildings on 27th Street between the Jockey Club and the newly
erected Brunswick Building are old stables; in a few more years
they will begin giving way to office buildings.
Probably about 1907.
Brown Brothers, Photographers.
NO REPRODUCTIONS..

721250f-a.title: Manhattan: Madison Avenue - 27th Street (East)
721250f-a.text:
Madison Avenue, east side, between 27th and 28th Streets, a new
building, replacing two small structures.
1923.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

721248f-a.title: Manhattan: Madison Avenue - 27th Street (East)
721248f-a.text:
63-71 Madison Avenue, east side, from 27th Street about halfway to
28th Street, showing a new office building 65-7 Madison Avenue,
nearing completion. It replaces two small houses.
Notice that Madison Avenue is temporarily a one-way street.
1923.
Dnift of E. M. Jenke.

711862f-a.title: Manhattan: 27th Street (East) - Madison Avenue
711862f-a.text:
East 27th Street, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Madison
Ave. In the foreground, in silhouette are sevoral of the pillars of the
old Madison Square Garden.
About 1920.
Gift of E. W. Jenks.
